        <p>We remark that one could now define a graph <inline-formula id="IEq301"><alternatives><tex-math id="M601">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\tilde{G}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M602"><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">~</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2021_186_Article_IEq301.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, obtained from <italic>G</italic> by inverting all long-reads <italic>r</italic> with a negative orientation <inline-formula id="IEq302"><alternatives><tex-math id="M603">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\varphi (r)=-1$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M604"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>φ</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2021_186_Article_IEq302.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. This amounts to replacing each long read <italic>r</italic> by its reverse complement. Since processing of the overlap graph does not explicitly consider the sequence information, it would be sufficient to replace the coordinates [<italic>p</italic>, <italic>q</italic>] of a match interval by <inline-formula id="IEq303"><alternatives><tex-math id="M605">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$[\ell -q+1,\ell -p+1]$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M606"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">[</mml:mo><mml:mi>ℓ</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>q</mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>ℓ</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">]</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2021_186_Article_IEq303.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and to invert the directionality of extension by another long read. The bit scores of matches, of course, remain unchanged. In <inline-formula id="IEq304"><alternatives><tex-math id="M607">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\tilde{G}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M608"><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">~</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2021_186_Article_IEq304.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> all edge signatures are <inline-formula id="IEq305"><alternatives><tex-math id="M609">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{\tilde{\theta }}}(e)=+1$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M610"><mml:mrow><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>θ</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2021_186_Article_IEq305.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. It is not necessary, however, to construct <inline-formula id="IEq306"><alternatives><tex-math id="M611">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\tilde{G}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M612"><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">~</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2021_186_Article_IEq306.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> explicitly. Instead, we simply keep track of the vertex orientations <inline-formula id="IEq307"><alternatives><tex-math id="M613">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\varphi (r)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M614"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>φ</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2021_186_Article_IEq307.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p>
        <p>From here on, we again write <italic>G</italic> for the orientable graph <inline-formula id="IEq308"><alternatives><tex-math id="M615">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$G'$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M616"><mml:msup><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mo>′</mml:mo></mml:msup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2021_186_Article_IEq308.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p>
      </sec>
    </sec>
    <sec id="Sec9">
      <title>Reduction to a directed acyclic graph</title>
      <p id="Par69">We next make use of the direction of extension of long read <inline-formula id="IEq309"><alternatives><tex-math id="M617">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$r_1$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M618"><mml:msub><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2021_186_Article_IEq309.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and <inline-formula id="IEq310"><alternatives><tex-math id="M619">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$r_2$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M620"><mml:msub><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2021_186_Article_IEq310.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> defined by the mutual overhangs in the case that <inline-formula id="IEq311"><alternatives><tex-math id="M621">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
