				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$s'$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M918"><mml:msup><mml:mi>s</mml:mi><mml:mo>′</mml:mo></mml:msup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2021_186_Article_IEq507.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, or a negative offset value if unitigs overlap. We take an arbitrary node in <italic>M</italic> and set its interval as the reference point. Positions of all other nodes are progressively built up following a topological order in this graph. If multiple edges exist between two nodes in this process an arbitrary but fixed edge is chosen to estimate the distance between nodes.</p>
      <p id="Par110">At this point, all sequence features are embedded in the same coordinate system. The reference contig is obtained as an in principle arbitrary projection of the read sequences. In practice, the short-read unitigs are used wherever available because of their much higher sequence quality. At the same time, we can map the features of each long read to their respective position in this newly constructed reference. This information can be directly fed into consensus based error correction systems such as racon [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR59">59</xref>].</p>
    </sec>
