  <sec id="Sec13">
    <title>Benchmarking</title>
    <p id="Par111">To demonstrate the feasibility of our assembly strategy we applied LazyB to data sets from previously published benchmarks of Nanopore assemblies. For yeast (<italic>S. cerevisiae</italic>) we used Nanopore sets ERR1883389 for lower coverage, ERR1883399 for higher coverage, and short-reads set ERR1938683, all from bioproject PRJEB19900 [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR60">60</xref>]. For comparison we used the reference genome R64.2.1 of strain S288C from the SGD. For fruit fly (<italic>D. melanogaster</italic>) we used the Oxford Nanopore and Illumina raw data of bioproject PRJNA433573 [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR61">61</xref>], and the FlyBase reference genome 6.30 (<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="http://www.flybase.org">http://www.flybase.org</ext-link>). For Human we uses accession SRX6356866-8 of bioproject PRJNA549351 [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR62">62</xref>] for long reads and SRA292482 [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR63">63</xref>] for short reads. Assemblies are compared against the NCBI reference genome GRCh38.p13.</p>
    <p id="Par112">Sequencing data were downsampled to approximately 5<inline-formula id="IEq520"><alternatives><tex-math id="M919">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
